User testing:

This week in user testing helped us to discover a number of potential problems as well as improvements that can be made to make the game more fun. One of the main concerns about the project was about the placement of each of the parts so that the user can easily reach across and touch those parts in very little time. The initial idea was to use a supporting structure that would hold up each of these parts. However we discovered that a single pole of wood wouldnt be able to withstand the force from any player especially while punching. 

Initial idea and changes:
The initial idea was to just use different fabrics and then let the blindfolded user use the fabrics for matching a piece of the game with the music. But from user feedback we realised that making it blindfolded would only make it more complicated especially when moving in front of a human sized structure. We gave up this idea and instead opted for playing the game without the blindfold. Some important points given during user feedback session:

1. Do not use blindfold
2. Have a supporting structure that is strong enough to withstand any force while playing the game
3. Make it easier to understand the game without any explaination with the help of feedback
4. Use different sensors for each body part instead of using only pressure sensors
5. Replace the human parts to make it look different.

Based on this feedback, we decided to laser cut each of the body parts and drill these onto a piece of wood. This way we can have independent parts like the finger and ear attached to their respective parts.

We started drawing different designs and testing for the best aesthetic appeal as well as retaining good usability. We spent a lot of time working on the design. Some of the drawings are below:

