We decided to split the tasks between ourseleves:
I decided to work on testing the sensors and writing the logic for the program. Federico and Eunice translated drawings from the paper to Illustrator.

Body parts and sensors:
1. The final body parts would be a face that we would like to project on with different expressions.
2. An ear into the user can blow into. This will have a piezo to detect the sound.
3. A stomach that the user can punch which uses a pressure sensor
4. A finger that can be pulled - detected using a stretch sensor
5. A tongue which can be flicked
6. A foot pedal that can be stamped on


Game design:
The game would ideally start when a player approaches the structure. Labels will be present under each body part indicating which part represents what. A voice would start saying commands and as the player performs those actions, the voice would express feelings such as "Ahh" or "Ohh" and the face would change to indicate those expressions. The time required to touch each part before the player loses decreases slowly making it harder. There is no end to the game. The player gets a score and the next player tries to beat the highest score. The code for the program to run on the Arduino can be found on github here <> and code to run on processing for running the game can be found <a href="">here.</a>

In order to simulate the game I designed it first running on my laptop using keyboard keys. I then extended this to include the sensors.

